FEEDFORWARD / LeakyReLU / LOB / Mean squared error (MSE)¶

  • Feedforward model with one hidden layer.

  • Trained just using LOB and not Liquidity measures: Input dimension is 60 x 21 = 1260

  • Mean squared error used as loss function.

  • Optimizer: Adam

  • Evaluation of: Epoch 4030

  • Training set consists of 202 days (~80%)

  • Validation set consists of 51 days (~20%)

Shown below:

  • Network structure

  • Settings used for training

  • Plots of model performance

import sys
sys.path.append('./../')
import numpy as np
from CODES.dataset.task_dataset import TaskDataset
filenames = os.listdir(cfg.DATA.DATA_PATH)
[filenames.pop(i) for i,k in enumerate(filenames) if k.split('.')[-1]!='npy'] #.DS_STORE problem
filenames.sort()
train_datanames = []
if cfg.DATA.PORTION is not None:
    filenames = filenames[:int(len(filenames)*cfg.DATA.PORTION)]
for filename in filenames:
    if len(train_datanames) < int(len(filenames)*cfg.TRAIN.SPLIT_RATIO):
        train_datanames.append(filename)
    else:
        break
    val_datanames = [i for i in filenames if not train_datanames.count(i)]
    train_dataset = TaskDataset(train_datanames)
    val_dataset = TaskDataset(val_datanames)
    
X_t = [] ; y_t = [] ; X_v = [] ; y_v = []
for i in range(len(train_datanames)):
    item = train_dataset.__getitem__(i)
    X_t.append(item['X']); y_t.append(item['y'])
for i in range(len(val_datanames)):
    item = val_dataset.__getitem__(i)
    X_v.append(item['X']); y_v.append(item['y'])


model.double();model.load_state_dict(ckpt['model_state'], strict=False);model.eval();torch.set_grad_enabled(False)

mid_pred = [] ; bid_pred = [] ; ask_pred = [] ; bid_var_pred = [] ; ask_var_pred = []
mid_pred_val = [] ; bid_pred_val = [] ; ask_pred_val = [] ; bid_var_pred_val = [] ; ask_var_pred_val = []

temp = []
for i in X_t:
    for k in i:
        temp.append(model(torch.reshape(k,(1,*k.shape)))[0])
#         temp = model(torch.reshape(k,(1,*k.shape)))[0]
#         mid_pred.append(temp[0])
#         bid_pred.append(temp[1])
#         ask_pred.append(temp[2])
#         bid_var_pred.append(temp[3])
#         ask_var_pred.append(temp[4])
temp_v = []     
for i in X_v:
    for k in i:
        temp_v.append(model(torch.reshape(k,(1,*k.shape)))[0])
#         temp = model(torch.reshape(k,(1,*k.shape)))[0]
#         mid_pred_val.append(temp[0])
#         bid_pred_val.append(temp[1])
#         ask_pred_val.append(temp[2])
#         bid_var_pred_val.append(temp[3])
#         ask_var_pred_val.append(temp[4])

for i,k in zip(temp,torch.cat(temp).reshape(-1,5)):
    if i.tolist() != k.tolist():
        raise Exception
for i,k in zip(temp_v,torch.cat(temp_v).reshape(-1,5)):
    if i.tolist() != k.tolist():
        raise Exception

# y_t_pred = torch.cat([*map(model,X_t)]) ; y_v_pred = torch.cat([*map(model,X_v)])
y_t_pred = torch.cat(temp).reshape(-1,5) ; y_v_pred = torch.cat(temp_v).reshape(-1,5)
y_t = torch.cat(y_t) ; y_v = torch.cat(y_v)

mse_train = [torch.mean((i-j)**2).numpy() for i,j in zip(y_t.transpose(1,0),y_t_pred.transpose(1,0))]
mse_val = [torch.mean((i-j)**2).numpy() for i,j in zip(y_v.transpose(1,0),y_v_pred.transpose(1,0))]
mape_train = [torch.mean(torch.abs(1-j/i)).numpy()*100 for i,j in zip(y_t.transpose(1,0),y_t_pred.transpose(1,0))]
mape_val = [torch.mean(torch.abs(1-j/i)).numpy()*100 for i,j in zip(y_v.transpose(1,0),y_v_pred.transpose(1,0))]

# mse_train = [np.round(torch.mean((i-j)**2).numpy(),4) for i,j in zip(y_t.transpose(1,0),y_t_pred.transpose(1,0))]
# mse_val = [np.round(torch.mean((i-j)**2).numpy(),4) for i,j in zip(y_v.transpose(1,0),y_v_pred.transpose(1,0))]
# mape_train = [np.round(torch.mean(torch.abs(1-j/i)).numpy()*100,2) for i,j in zip(y_t.transpose(1,0),y_t_pred.transpose(1,0))]
# mape_val = [np.round(torch.mean(torch.abs(1-j/i)).numpy()*100,2) for i,j in zip(y_v.transpose(1,0),y_v_pred.transpose(1,0))]

Evaluation plots¶

Below we have five plots for five different variables we wanted to predict. They are created by plotting the training and prediction performance of the model throughout the year for each day's trading window, which goes from the 61st trading minute until the last trading minute of the day.

These windows are ordered and stacked, starting from the first trading day's window until the last day's trading window.

On the x-axis we always have the minutes and on the y-axis the corresponding variable of the plot.
